violation_comments: Basement and 1st floor - missing smoke detectors.
violation_code_book_text: Install and maintain approved smoke detectors. (13-196-100 thru 13-196-160) Install a smoke detector in every dwelling unit. Install one on any living level with a habitable room or unenclosed heating plant, on the uppermost ceiling of enclosed porch stairwell, and within 15 feet of every sleeping room. Be sure the detector is at least 4 inches from the wall, 4 to 12 inches from the ceiling, and not above door or window.

violation_comments: Basement and 1st floor - missing carbon monoxide detectors.
violation_code_book_text: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

violation_comments:
The rear porch at (5507-09) is a 3 story wood porch. The footings appear to be set on slab and do not appear to extend below the frost line. Both structural columns are over notch cut. The column nearest the alley that is non-treated lumber has areas of wood rot. That column has a severely separated structural lap joint (failure) at the 2cd level. The column secttions for both column arrays are joined with sub-standard (1/4"-3/8") bolts that are rusted. 
The stair stringers are over notch cut. Plans and permit required to repair or replace this porch.
violation_code_book_text: Failed to rebuild or replace dilapidated and dangerous porch.  (13-196-570, 13-196-641)

violation_comments: Rear, 3 - 3 story open wood porches (total of 4 rear 3 story open wood porches) 5501-5509 W. Huron/654-656 N. Pine - Foundations unknown, columns over notched with beams notched into 6x6 and 4x4 columns, beams mostly are only nailed into columns - some are bolted, but the bolts are rusting.  Deck joists only nailed into single header rim beams, some have rusted joists hangers (very deteriorated) 4x4 column splices only nailed, stair stringers only nailed to header joists and columns - weak and unstable, stair treads are loose, rotted, worn and split, guard and handrails - only nailed to columns - some are loose.  These 3 porches are dangerous and hazardous.  Plans and permits required to replace all 3 porches.  (5507-09 W. Huron - porch written in original complaint, item #1).
violation_code_book_text: Failed to rebuild or replace dilapidated and dangerous porch.  (13-196-570, 13-196-641)

violation_comments: Basement - missing carbon monoxide detector.
violation_code_book_text: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.

violation_comments: Entire building,including basement heating plant room,7755 apartment 3,7753 apartment 1 thru 3- carbon monoxide detectors missing.
violation_code_book_text: Install carbon monoxide detector within 40 feet of every sleeping room in residential structure. (13-64-190, 13-64-210) A carbon monoxide detector is needed whenever there is a heating appliance on the premises that burns fossil fuel such as gas, oil, or coal, or air that is circulated through a heat exchanger. Install according to manufacturer instructions. A hard wired model requires an electrical wiring permit. In a single family residence, be sure the detector is on or below the lowest floor with a place to sleep. In a multiple dwelling residence heated by a boiler, install a detector in the same room as the boiler. Otherwise, each apartment follows single family guidelines. The owner is responsible for installation and written instructions, the tenant for testing, maintenance, and batteries.
